WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.295 --> 00:00:17.080
<v Mike Demopoulos> Hello and welcome back to the 
WP Accessibility Day, one o'clock a.m. UTC session.

2
00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:21.440
If you have any questions, our chat moderator 
Kayla will be answering them.

3
00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:24.989
So please put the questions that you have 
for our speaker. 

4
00:00:24.989 --> 00:00:32.532
Please remember that we are welcoming community 
and there is a code of conduct in force during this entire event. 

5
00:00:32.532 --> 00:00:36.474
You can find slides and Twitter links, 
all the information 

6
00:00:36.474 --> 00:00:39.040
on our website at wpaccessibilityday.org.

7
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.705
Our speaker right now is Adam. 

8
00:00:42.705 --> 00:00:47.680
Adam is a Web Developer at the University of Connecticut,

9
00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.937
or UConn, in the role at the 
Office of University Communications. 

10
00:00:52.937 --> 00:00:57.523
He specializes in WordPress Application Development 
and Web Accessibility. 


11
00:00:57.523 --> 00:01:02.452
He's also been on the Accessibility and Diversity 
Committees at UConn. 

12
00:01:02.452 --> 00:01:07.520
These include UConn's 
Innovation and Communication Technology Task Force

13
00:01:07.520 --> 00:01:12.739
and University Communications Diversity, Equity, 
and Inclusion Task Force. 

14
00:01:12.739 --> 00:01:19.275
When he's not working he enjoys reading, 
martial arts, and spending time with his family. 

15
00:01:19.275 --> 00:01:25.840
It's my pleasure to welcome Adam and his talk, 
Accessible Navigation from Scratch.

16
00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:30.773
<v Adam Berkowitz> Hi everybody. 
Let me see if I can get my screen shared, 

17
00:01:30.773 --> 00:01:34.400
make sure this works correctly. 

18
00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:39.388
I think that should do it. Okay, excellent. 

19
00:01:39.388 --> 00:01:47.600
Thank you very much for that terrific introduction
and thank you all for being here with me.

20
00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:54.000
I hope that you've enjoyed everything so far 
and learned a lot from the other presenters today.

21
00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.929
The web team in our office focuses on top level 
and strategic marketing sites, 

22
00:02:00.929 --> 00:02:05.087
such as uconn.edu which is our main university website, 

23
00:02:05.087 --> 00:02:08.800
our regional campus websites and 
hospital network.

24
00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:13.104
As you can imagine, these get a lot of traffic 

25
00:02:13.104 --> 00:02:16.570
and we need to make sure that they are as accessible 

26
00:02:16.570 --> 00:02:19.840
and welcoming as possible to everyone who visits.

27
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:29.440
A few years ago, the World Accessibility Day 
New England Conference was held at the university.

28
00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:33.280
Pretty much everyone from our office's 
web team attended.

29
00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:40.080
As the conference went on, it became very obvious, 
very quickly, how much work we needed to do.

30
00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:45.680
One of the things we looked at on our sites, 
was the main navigation components.

31
00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:51.029
As a state institution, 
we had some pretty specific requirements. 

32
00:02:51.029 --> 00:02:57.522
For instance, I think that at the time 
we were still supporting Internet Explorer 10 

33
00:02:57.522 --> 00:03:01.741
and we also wanted to make sure that, for instance, 

34
00:03:01.741 --> 00:03:06.610
people could use the navigation elements without JavaScript 

35
00:03:06.610 --> 00:03:10.520
and we wanted to make sure that we were in compliance

36
00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:13.988
with all the relevant state and federal laws. 

37
00:03:13.988 --> 00:03:20.384
And we also wanted to do the right thing and have 
our websites be as good as they could be. 

38
00:03:20.384 --> 00:03:28.811
One of the things after that conference was, I wanted 
to improve these navigational elements which leads us here today. 

39
00:03:28.811 --> 00:03:33.002
Now I'd like to point out that this project 
and presentation 

40
00:03:33.002 --> 00:03:36.070
are based on the majority of the needs for sites

41
00:03:36.070 --> 00:03:39.394
currently in use at the University of Connecticut. 

42
00:03:39.394 --> 00:03:44.137
Even if you choose not to use the specific approach I'll show you, 

43
00:03:44.137 --> 00:03:48.000
the basic ideas can be adapted to a wide range of sites.

44
00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:53.284
Now unless you're building a site which is only one page, 

45
00:03:53.284 --> 00:03:56.949
people are going to have to find their way around 

46
00:03:56.949 --> 00:04:00.205
and not only that, but as a web developer 

47
00:04:00.205 --> 00:04:05.863
I know that if I put something or 
really anything interactive on a site, 

48
00:04:05.863 --> 00:04:08.729
people are going to try and use it. 

49
00:04:08.729 --> 00:04:13.498
That means interactive elements may get used in ways 

50
00:04:13.498 --> 00:04:17.187
that are unexpected or unfamiliar to me. 

51
00:04:17.187 --> 00:04:20.724
As developers, just like we validate forum inputs, 

52
00:04:20.724 --> 00:04:25.440
because we can't anticipate every single thing someone might enter,

53
00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:32.588
we need to consider how people will use our sites 
besides with a mouse and screen. 

54
00:04:32.588 --> 00:04:37.155
In terms of accessibility, this concept applies to visitors 

55
00:04:37.155 --> 00:04:40.808
with permanent disabilities first and foremost. 

56
00:04:40.808 --> 00:04:43.523
At the same time, some visitors may have 

57
00:04:43.523 --> 00:04:48.092
a temporary or contextual accessibility need 
with respect to a site. 

58
00:04:48.092 --> 00:04:53.920
Their mouse might break, they might be working 
on an airplane going through turbulence,

59
00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:56.856
their dominant hand might be broken, 

60
00:04:56.856 --> 00:05:01.029
or maybe they visited an eye doctor and 
got their pupils dilated.

61
00:05:01.029 --> 00:05:06.560
We just can't know. We can't know the situation 
for every single person who visits us,

62
00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:11.616
but we can try to design, build, 
and prepare sites 

63
00:05:11.616 --> 00:05:14.080
in the most equitable ways we can.

64
00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:17.494
So how can we make sure this happens? 

65
00:05:17.494 --> 00:05:19.680
Well we try to keep our sites POUR.

66
00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:25.360
You may have heard or seen 
this acronym POUR in the past,

67
00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:30.787
but what does it mean in the 
context of a navigation menu? 

68
00:05:30.787 --> 00:05:36.242
In my view, Perceivable means 
if a visitor can physically see the menu,

69
00:05:36.242 --> 00:05:40.160
it must be visible or be able to be made visible.

70
00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:44.258
If that visitor can't physically see the menu, 

71
00:05:44.258 --> 00:05:47.280
a screen reader should detect and announce items.

72
00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:54.351
For the menu to be Operable, someone should be able to interact with it, 

73
00:05:54.351 --> 00:05:57.222
with the mouse and or the keyboard. 

74
00:05:57.222 --> 00:06:01.181
If someone uses a mouse and there are sub-menus, 

75
00:06:01.181 --> 00:06:03.362
they need to be resilient. 

76
00:06:03.362 --> 00:06:07.228
That is, the sub-menus can't disappear immediately.

77
00:06:07.228 --> 00:06:10.098
Further, all the items in a sub-menu 

78
00:06:10.098 --> 00:06:13.899
need to be reachable with a mouse or a keyboard. 

79
00:06:13.899 --> 00:06:16.832
For the menu to be Understandable, 

80
00:06:16.832 --> 00:06:20.100
it should behave in a predictable way. 

81
00:06:20.100 --> 00:06:22.823
Therefore, it needs to maintain 

82
00:06:22.823 --> 00:06:25.631
visual and auditory consistency. 

83
00:06:25.631 --> 00:06:29.039
For instance, if an icon toggles between two states, 

84
00:06:29.039 --> 00:06:32.640
such as open and closed, it should do that predictably.

85
00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:35.790
Menu items should announce themselves 

86
00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:38.960
in a predictable way for people who use screen readers.

87
00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:43.927
Finally for the menu to be Robust, in our case, 

88
00:06:43.927 --> 00:06:50.537
we wanted to ensure that it would work 
at least to some degree without JavaScript 

89
00:06:50.537 --> 00:06:52.988
and this meant keeping the style 

90
00:06:52.988 --> 00:06:56.255
and user experience approximately the same, 

91
00:06:56.255 --> 00:06:59.040
as if there were JavaScript available.

92
00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:04.389
In order to accomplish these goals, 
we identified 

93
00:07:04.389 --> 00:07:09.600
three cases for menu items that are typical 
for the types of site we build.

94
00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:16.201
Overall, I think these cases 
are pretty common. 

95
00:07:16.201 --> 00:07:21.556
First a link by itself which we can easily 
rely on WordPress to handle. 

96
00:07:21.556 --> 00:07:25.200
After that we identified 
two types of sub-menus.

97
00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:28.747
Those that have a link 
to a top level page

98
00:07:28.747 --> 00:07:36.568
with sub-pages beneath and 
menu items that need to solely act 

99
00:07:36.568 --> 00:07:39.840
as a toggle to a series of sub-items.

100
00:07:41.280 --> 00:07:45.365
These are fairly typical types of 
elements in a nav menu. 

101
00:07:45.365 --> 00:07:48.789
Either you want to go somewhere
by following a link, 

102
00:07:48.789 --> 00:07:51.050
or you want to reveal more choices 

103
00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:53.440
through some kind of toggling action.

104
00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:59.360
Now that we've got our goals through 
the POUR acronym and our cases,

105
00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:04.320
we need to have a good idea of 
what elements are available to build with.

106
00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:10.244
Before we try to style anything
or provide interaction, 

107
00:08:10.244 --> 00:08:14.471
we need to get a handle on 
the HTML tags and properties we want 

108
00:08:14.471 --> 00:08:17.840
and how they're going to 
get rendered to the page.

109
00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:22.615
This actually has a massive impact on

110
00:08:22.615 --> 00:08:26.720
all the decisions that get made later.

111
00:08:26.720 --> 00:08:31.554
For instance, the style, JavaScript, 
everything else that comes after. 

112
00:08:31.554 --> 00:08:36.102
If we don't have a good concept of 
what we have at the beginning 

113
00:08:36.102 --> 00:08:41.588
and where we're trying to go, 
then we won't be able to add on. 

114
00:08:41.588 --> 00:08:49.600
Fortunately, WordPress has a built-in way to 
generate a menu with the wp_nav_menu function.

115
00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:55.156
I'm sure that many of you 
are familiar with this.

116
00:08:55.156 --> 00:08:57.825
The good news is that wp_ nav_menu

117
00:08:57.825 --> 00:09:00.807
is easy to use and get started with. 

118
00:09:00.807 --> 00:09:03.187
It accepts a list of arguments 

119
00:09:03.187 --> 00:09:07.179
that provide a fair amount of customization quickly 

120
00:09:07.179 --> 00:09:12.400
and then after that, as soon as the page loads, 
it displays a menu.

121
00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:17.768
One argument which I tend to change immediately,

122
00:09:17.768 --> 00:09:20.060
is the container argument. 

123
00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:23.528
By default, the menu will be contained by a div. 

124
00:09:23.528 --> 00:09:27.280
This isn't ideal for a navigation menu of this type,

125
00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:33.200
because a div doesn't impart any 
structure or meaning on its own, 

126
00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:36.750
but you can set the container to a nav element. 

127
00:09:36.750 --> 00:09:40.465
When you do this the 
final output of the menu

128
00:09:40.465 --> 00:09:42.968
will be wrapped in a nav tag. 

129
00:09:42.968 --> 00:09:46.370
Browsers will then detect the tag and create 

130
00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:49.848
an implicit ARIA role for it, with a landmark.

131
00:09:49.848 --> 00:09:53.211
This is a useful accessibility improvement, 

132
00:09:53.211 --> 00:09:56.786
because a screen reader will have an easier time

133
00:09:56.786 --> 00:09:59.244
parsing the document's content. 

134
00:09:59.244 --> 00:10:04.160
There are other arguments which 
you may be familiar with as well.

135
00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:07.429
For instance, you can set custom classes, 

136
00:10:07.429 --> 00:10:09.920
or IDs, or set a theme location.

137
00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:14.396
Depending on how many navigation sections you have on the page, 

138
00:10:14.396 --> 00:10:19.299
you might also set the container, 
or ARIA label argument as well, 

139
00:10:19.299 --> 00:10:22.080
to further clarify the menu's purpose.

140
00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:27.303
Now wp_nav_menu works really well for menus

141
00:10:27.303 --> 00:10:30.787
that have only one level of content. 

142
00:10:30.787 --> 00:10:33.317
However, once you add depth to the menu, 

143
00:10:33.317 --> 00:10:35.600
you'll run into accessibility issues.

144
00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:39.274
Let's take a look at how wp_nav_menu

145
00:10:39.274 --> 00:10:42.640
interprets each of the three cases I shared,

146
00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:48.302
then we can see how we might 
improve their accessibility. 

147
00:10:48.302 --> 00:10:52.230
The markup for a plain link 
is pretty straightforward. 

148
00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:56.800
WordPress gives us just what we need, 
an anchor tag with a URL.

149
00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:00.415
This will provide a nice accessible link 

150
00:11:00.415 --> 00:11:04.010
that supports people who use keyboard navigation

151
00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:07.005
and/or screen readers. 
So far so good. 

152
00:11:07.005 --> 00:11:10.400
After this, things start to get complicated.

153
00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:16.278
In this case, we want to provide the ability 

154
00:11:16.278 --> 00:11:20.702
to either click on a top-level link to visit a page 

155
00:11:20.702 --> 00:11:23.391
or access items in a sub-menu. 

156
00:11:23.391 --> 00:11:29.933
As the markup is now though, 
we run into a couple of things that could be better. 

157
00:11:29.933 --> 00:11:33.513
First, the aria-label attribute on the link 

158
00:11:33.513 --> 00:11:36.361
takes precedence for screen readers

159
00:11:36.361 --> 00:11:40.070
over the content inside of 
the anchor tag. 

160
00:11:40.070 --> 00:11:42.732
Instead of a screen reader saying 

161
00:11:42.732 --> 00:11:46.042
the inner text of the link which is About Us, 

162
00:11:46.042 --> 00:11:50.427
it will say the value of the aria-label which is just sub-menu. 

163
00:11:50.427 --> 00:11:52.717
That's not terribly descriptive, 

164
00:11:52.717 --> 00:11:55.840
because someone might want to click the link.

165
00:11:57.280 --> 00:12:04.000
Next, aria-haspopup will announce to a screen reader
that a pop-up is available,

166
00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:07.832
but we're missing supporting ARIA attributes 

167
00:12:07.832 --> 00:12:11.200
to associate the link with a specific sub-menu and

168
00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:14.659
indicate if that sub-menu is open or closed. 

169
00:12:14.659 --> 00:12:19.040
Last, depending on how the sub-menu is hidden and shown,

170
00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:25.051
there might be no good way for people who use a keyboard 
to get to it effectively. 

171
00:12:25.051 --> 00:12:29.984
In addition, aside from showing the sub-menu 
when the mouse hovers over the list element, 

172
00:12:29.984 --> 00:12:32.478
it's not clear how we can open the sub-menu. 

173
00:12:32.478 --> 00:12:37.995
If we click on the link, it'll take us to the page 
and never open the sub-menu. 

174
00:12:37.995 --> 00:12:41.835
If we just want the top nav item to work as a toggle, 

175
00:12:41.835 --> 00:12:43.947
we can use a hash symbol as the link.

176
00:12:43.947 --> 00:12:47.223
Of course then we need to use JavaScript to prevent it from 

177
00:12:47.223 --> 00:12:49.625
reloading the page when the link is clicked 

178
00:12:49.625 --> 00:12:53.680
and this is something that internally at our department 
we wanted to avoid.

179
00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:57.818
However, if we get rid of the href attribute 

180
00:12:57.818 --> 00:13:00.640
by removing any link from the admin area,

181
00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.462
the item can't be focused with a keyboard. 

182
00:13:03.462 --> 00:13:06.480
Browsers will interpret anchor tags without an

183
00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:10.549
href property like a span or any other inline element. 

184
00:13:10.549 --> 00:13:14.202
So we can add non-JavaScript dependent toggles 

185
00:13:14.202 --> 00:13:17.077
to list of issues we need to handle. 

186
00:13:17.077 --> 00:13:21.040
Now I'd like to show you what we'd like to add,

187
00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:24.743
how we're going to get there, and what the result is. 

188
00:13:24.743 --> 00:13:28.080
At this point, what I wanted was a portable, 

189
00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:31.491
flexible, robust set of choices to build off. 

190
00:13:31.491 --> 00:13:35.013
That included things like being able to distinguish 

191
00:13:35.013 --> 00:13:38.805
between links that go somewhere and toggles that don't. 

192
00:13:38.805 --> 00:13:43.470
More ARIA attributes to support 
people who use screen readers, 

193
00:13:43.470 --> 00:13:45.840
custom classes, icons and so on.

194
00:13:46.960 --> 00:13:51.706
WordPress does provide some 
additional filters for navigation menus 

195
00:13:51.706 --> 00:13:55.724
such as wp_nav_menu items, 
wp_nav_menu_object filters. 

196
00:13:55.724 --> 00:13:58.436
However, I wanted to be able to create

197
00:13:58.436 --> 00:14:02.289
the same kinds of markup across a variety of themes. 

198
00:14:02.289 --> 00:14:06.000
For us, this would help with our brand consistency and

199
00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.264
visitor expectation from one site to the next. 

200
00:14:09.264 --> 00:14:12.320
Fortunately, we can tap into an override the

201
00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:14.433
core class wp_nav_menu uses 

202
00:14:14.433 --> 00:14:17.904
to generate the output for a navigation menu. 

203
00:14:17.904 --> 00:14:20.656
We can do this with a custom Walker class. 

204
00:14:20.656 --> 00:14:24.880
To make it portable we can then 
turn that into a Composer package

205
00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:27.802
that can be installed from GitHub or Packagist.


206
00:14:27.802 --> 00:14:30.480
The project can then be used in many places.

207
00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:36.464
The Walker_Nav_Menu class 
is part of a collection of Walkers 

208
00:14:36.464 --> 00:14:41.032
which all inherit their functionality from a general Walker class. 

209
00:14:41.032 --> 00:14:45.969
Now to be completely honest, 
when I started looking into this back then, 

210
00:14:45.969 --> 00:14:48.539
the Walkers were incredibly confusing.

211
00:14:48.539 --> 00:14:53.184
Fortunately, these classes take care of a lot of the work for us though. 

212
00:14:53.184 --> 00:14:58.080
For example, we don't have 
to worry about writing our own recursive functions

213
00:14:58.080 --> 00:15:01.862
to traverse menu structure since that's 
their main purpose. 

214
00:15:01.862 --> 00:15:05.672
Rather we can focus on logic 
for the markup our menu might need 

215
00:15:05.672 --> 00:15:07.840
and what the output should look like.

216
00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:12.740
Once you write your custom Walker class 

217
00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:16.880
you can then add it to the 
list of arguments used by wp_nav_menu.

218
00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:22.240
When you do this, all the 
markup created by wp_nav_menu

219
00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.615
will flow through the Custom Walker. 

220
00:15:24.615 --> 00:15:27.963
This means that you can override any of the 

221
00:15:27.963 --> 00:15:31.082
Walker Nav Menu's methods with your own, 

222
00:15:31.082 --> 00:15:33.973
and that's what wp_nav_menu will use. 

223
00:15:33.973 --> 00:15:38.578
There are four class methods available 
which will let you start a level, 

224
00:15:38.578 --> 00:15:41.840
start an element, end an element and end a level.

225
00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:45.534
In this context, we only need two of those. 

226
00:15:45.534 --> 00:15:48.560
The one to start a level and start an element.

227
00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:56.662
Every item in the menu is going to pass through 
the start_el and end_el methods.

228
00:15:56.662 --> 00:15:59.748
These methods are where we can add logic 

229
00:15:59.748 --> 00:16:03.360
to support the type of markup we want to build.

230
00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:09.280
Consequently, the start-el method was where 
most of the work for my custom Walker happened.

231
00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:13.244
However, we're not just dealing with a flat menu, 

232
00:16:13.244 --> 00:16:15.520
we need to be able to add depth as well.

233
00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.852
When we create a nested sub-menu, 

234
00:16:19.852 --> 00:16:23.440
the Walker will pass the output for the markup

235
00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:26.500
through the start and end level methods as well. 

236
00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:28.560
These create the unordered lists.

237
00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:36.640
We can take advantage of that to affect 
how the submenu unordered list elements get created.

238
00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:43.600
In terms of accessibility, we can make sure 
we're adding useful IDs to each level for example.

239
00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:47.687
By default WordPress wasn't doing this, 

240
00:16:47.687 --> 00:16:50.646
or at least I don't remember it doing it 

241
00:16:50.646 --> 00:16:53.609
back when I started this. It may do it now. 

242
00:16:53.609 --> 00:16:56.409
This will let us match up the sub-menu 

243
00:16:56.409 --> 00:16:59.711
to an aria-owns property in the items markup. 

244
00:16:59.711 --> 00:17:04.880
Now that we've seen the path 
the markup takes through the Walker class,

245
00:17:04.880 --> 00:17:08.880
let's zoom in to the start_el method 
where most of the logic happens.

246
00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:16.000
Here I've written out some pseudo code 
to describe the flow through our custom start_el  method.

247
00:17:17.040 --> 00:17:20.960
The shell of this is exactly what you would see 
if you took a look at the Walker.

248
00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:26.297
We can start by checking to see if the current item has children. 

249
00:17:26.297 --> 00:17:31.550
That is, should it be a link by itself, 
or should it have a sub-menu with it?

250
00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:34.331
If not, if it's just a link by itself, 

251
00:17:34.331 --> 00:17:37.150
we can output the start of a list item 

252
00:17:37.150 --> 00:17:39.680
with a link inside and then finish.

253
00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:44.662
Otherwise, we need to know if the top level item

254
00:17:44.662 --> 00:17:46.880
should be a link or a button.

255
00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.089
If it doesn't have a link, we can output

256
00:17:51.089 --> 00:17:54.720
the start of a list item with a button on the inside.

257
00:17:55.920 --> 00:18:01.296
Otherwise, we need both a link 
and then a button as a sibling. 

258
00:18:01.296 --> 00:18:05.481
This way we can account 
for all the cases in the markup. 

259
00:18:05.481 --> 00:18:09.357
With this logic in place,
we can also do things like 

260
00:18:09.357 --> 00:18:12.658
add additional custom classes and data attributes. 

261
00:18:12.658 --> 00:18:16.800
Those can help us style and interact with the menu more easily.

262
00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.525
Let's look at some examples of the output 

263
00:18:21.525 --> 00:18:24.886
that the custom Walker I wrote, creates. 

264
00:18:24.886 --> 00:18:28.083
So here we're back at our plain link, 

265
00:18:28.083 --> 00:18:31.858
but notice that we've added prefixed am dash classes

266
00:18:31.858 --> 00:18:35.416
in addition to the standard WordPress 
classes. 

267
00:18:35.416 --> 00:18:38.320
These will help designers and developers

268
00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:41.452
create styles specifically for these types of menus 

269
00:18:41.452 --> 00:18:43.680
without relying on WordPress classes.

270
00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:47.904
There's also a no-js class on the element. 

271
00:18:47.904 --> 00:18:51.280
The no-js class will be removed from the markup

272
00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:53.993
if the menu's JavaScript is available. 

273
00:18:53.993 --> 00:18:56.080
If the JavaScript doesn't run,

274
00:18:56.080 --> 00:18:58.175
this class will provide a fail safe 

275
00:18:58.175 --> 00:19:01.200
for opening and closing sub-menus 
as I'll show soon.

276
00:19:03.760 --> 00:19:06.377
Here's how we can improve the markup 

277
00:19:06.377 --> 00:19:08.640
for linked items with sub-menus.

278
00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:16.480
First, instead of the link's 
aria-label only saying sub-menu,

279
00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:18.709
it now describes the text of the link 

280
00:19:18.709 --> 00:19:21.760
and gives a hint about how 
you can interact with it.

281
00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:24.520
You can obviously change this 

282
00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.159
to whatever is appropriate for you. 

283
00:19:27.159 --> 00:19:29.860
Next, the button is going to provide 

284
00:19:29.860 --> 00:19:32.415
a semantically appropriate element 

285
00:19:32.415 --> 00:19:36.983
that we can interact with whether 
JavaScript is available or not. 

286
00:19:36.983 --> 00:19:40.720
We've also added a couple more ARIA attributes to it.

287
00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:45.614
Aria-expanded will indicate 
to a screen reader 

288
00:19:45.614 --> 00:19:48.000
if the sub-menu is open or not.

289
00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:53.199
We can change its state with JavaScript later. 

290
00:19:53.199 --> 00:19:57.068
Since we don't want any text to show on the button, 

291
00:19:57.068 --> 00:20:01.085
we need to give it an 
aria-label to provide context. 

292
00:20:01.085 --> 00:20:04.085
This is in case the button is focused. 

293
00:20:04.085 --> 00:20:08.240
Inside the button we can then make space for an icon.

294
00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:12.418
Here we can use the aria-hidden property. 

295
00:20:12.418 --> 00:20:16.080
The aria-hidden property will hide only the icon

296
00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:19.848
from screen readers, but still leave it visually available. 

297
00:20:19.848 --> 00:20:23.302
Since we've created screen reader accessible text 

298
00:20:23.302 --> 00:20:26.272
on the button with the aria-label property 

299
00:20:26.272 --> 00:20:28.800
and added the aria-expanded property,

300
00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:33.756
we can use aria-hidden 
to hide the icon without a problem. 

301
00:20:33.756 --> 00:20:37.562
The aria-owns property will associate the button 

302
00:20:37.562 --> 00:20:44.441
with the sub-menu, 
with the aria-owns property or the correct ID, rather. 

303
00:20:44.441 --> 00:20:48.499
This works in a way similar to how a label

304
00:20:48.499 --> 00:20:51.977
is associated with a form element. 

305
00:20:51.977 --> 00:20:55.408
This is now markup that will let a visitor choose

306
00:20:55.408 --> 00:20:59.120
between clicking on a link or opening up a sub-menu.

307
00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:04.467
In the last case, there is no link for the item. 


308
00:21:04.467 --> 00:21:09.956
It's replaced entirely by a button, so it can always act as a toggle. 

309
00:21:09.956 --> 00:21:14.112
You can imagine that if you combine all these cases, 

310
00:21:14.112 --> 00:21:18.828
you can start to get a very flexible and accessible menu, 

311
00:21:18.828 --> 00:21:21.268
but we're not quite done yet. 

312
00:21:21.268 --> 00:21:26.224
So far we've made sure that people 
will be able to interact with the menu 

313
00:21:26.224 --> 00:21:29.840
with a mouse, keyboard, and a screen reader.

314
00:21:30.560 --> 00:21:34.800
Now we have to think a little bit more 
about design and interaction.

315
00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:40.480
In our context, we wanted menus 
to work primarily through toggling actions.

316
00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:47.160
Actually, as I was writing this, I forgot one thing 

317
00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:49.680
and I added this slide today.

318
00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:51.871
As I was preparing the presentation

319
00:21:51.871 --> 00:21:54.000
 I realized I had made a mistake.

320
00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:58.415
In the navigation menu you want to have 

321
00:21:58.415 --> 00:22:01.770
the current page and/or its top level parent 

322
00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:04.006
visually highlighted somehow, 

323
00:22:04.006 --> 00:22:07.415
and this lets people know which page is active. 

324
00:22:07.415 --> 00:22:09.681
WordPress gives classes for this, 

325
00:22:09.681 --> 00:22:11.747
but also you want to make sure 

326
00:22:11.747 --> 00:22:14.880
that the aria-current property is set on pages.

327
00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:20.080
Prior to WordPress 5.3, I think, 
you had to do this manually.

328
00:22:20.720 --> 00:22:26.800
Typically, you could do this 
with the nav_menu_link attributes filter,

329
00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:32.252
but in checking, this filter doesn't seem to work 
with the custom Walker I created. 

330
00:22:32.252 --> 00:22:34.550
I'm not entirely sure why right now, 

331
00:22:34.550 --> 00:22:38.525
so I'm going to have to go back and refine it, 
but that's okay. 

332
00:22:38.525 --> 00:22:42.990
I think the more important thing is 
to note that even while trying my best, 

333
00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.418
I still ended up missing something by accident, 

334
00:22:45.418 --> 00:22:48.960
which is all the more reason for me 
to keep learning and researching.

335
00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:56.077
Now I'm not going to go over 
everything in the CSS for this project,

336
00:22:56.077 --> 00:23:01.318
but rather focus on CSS related to hiding and showing content. 

337
00:23:01.318 --> 00:23:04.811
When we use CSS to hide and show content, 

338
00:23:04.811 --> 00:23:10.299
our choices affect how people,
who use screen readers and keyboards, 

339
00:23:10.299 --> 00:23:13.739
can or cannot interact with web content. 

340
00:23:13.739 --> 00:23:17.589
The ability to show and hide content 
is an important part of 

341
00:23:17.589 --> 00:23:20.240
user interface and user experience design.

342
00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:24.105
This is especially true for navigation menus 

343
00:23:24.105 --> 00:23:28.730
where we often want to hide or show content on hover or focus. 

344
00:23:28.730 --> 00:23:32.598
If we're not careful, we can inadvertently use CSS 

345
00:23:32.598 --> 00:23:35.938
to create an inaccessible experience for our visitors. 

346
00:23:35.938 --> 00:23:38.480
So I think that it's important to understand

347
00:23:38.480 --> 00:23:43.360
the accessibility implications of 
how we use CSS to accomplish this.

348
00:23:44.720 --> 00:23:47.790
There's several cases where this chart is important. 

349
00:23:47.790 --> 00:23:51.875
We might consider the case where a visitor who uses a screen reader 

350
00:23:51.875 --> 00:23:54.254
wants to skim all the links on a site. 

351
00:23:54.254 --> 00:23:58.825
We should be aware that if we use 
display: none or visibility: hidden, 

352
00:23:58.825 --> 00:24:01.183
we'll be hiding content from them. 

353
00:24:01.183 --> 00:24:03.525
Another visitor may come to our site

354
00:24:03.525 --> 00:24:07.884
and have an issue with motor control 
and browse with a keyboard. 

355
00:24:07.884 --> 00:24:10.984
Depending on how we hide and show content, 

356
00:24:10.984 --> 00:24:15.887
our choices may make that user experience 
more or less accessible. 

357
00:24:15.887 --> 00:24:19.780
If the links in the navigation menu 
can be found in other ways

358
00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:22.884
or duplicated somewhere, 
that may not be a problem. 

359
00:24:22.884 --> 00:24:24.921
But we should think about our choices

360
00:24:24.921 --> 00:24:27.840
and the overall context 
of the site as we make them.

361
00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.247
One of the design requirements as 
I've said for our menus, 

362
00:24:33.247 --> 00:24:36.968
was that some menus should be open and closed by toggle. 

363
00:24:36.968 --> 00:24:39.840
The usual way to do this is with JavaScript,

364
00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:43.760
so that when someone clicks on the menu item, 
the sub-menu is shown or hidden.

365
00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:48.480
However, we can't predict if people 
will have JavaScript available to them.

366
00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:54.000
Some people may choose to not use JavaScript. 
They may block it entirely.

367
00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:57.990
There may be a delay getting JavaScript to someone, 

368
00:24:57.990 --> 00:25:02.761
or there may be an error that 
prevents JavaScript from loading correctly. 

369
00:25:02.761 --> 00:25:05.920
If we're going to hide the sub-menus or content,

370
00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:11.040
we should still think about how we can 
give people a way to access those items.

371
00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:14.537
One way to do this is the focus-within 

372
00:25:14.537 --> 00:25:17.280
pseudo class which I'll describe in a moment.

373
00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:21.360
You should be aware though, that focus-within

374
00:25:21.360 --> 00:25:23.691
isn't supported by Internet Explorer 

375
00:25:23.691 --> 00:25:26.400
or non-chromium versions of Microsoft Edge.

376
00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.720
According to the analytics 
I looked at for our sites,

377
00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:33.440
this represented a small 
percentage of our visitors.

378
00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:37.250
Further, this pseudo class will only be used 

379
00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:40.000
in the event that JavaScript fails altogether.

380
00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:43.981
I think that the browser restrictions 

381
00:25:43.981 --> 00:25:47.928
are a fair trade-off to get a very similar effect. 

382
00:25:47.928 --> 00:25:51.456
Now if the JavaScript does not run correctly 

383
00:25:51.456 --> 00:25:56.160
the no-js class and its styles will be applied to the menu.

384
00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:59.033
This includes the focus-within pseudo class. 

385
00:25:59.033 --> 00:26:02.480
The Mozilla developer network says that focus-within,

386
00:26:03.840 --> 00:26:07.040
"represents an element that has received focus 

387
00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:10.240
or contains an element that has received focus.

388
00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:14.210
In other words, it represents an element that is 

389
00:26:14.210 --> 00:26:17.048
itself matched by the focus pseudo class or 


390
00:26:17.048 --> 00:26:19.760
has a descendant that is matched by focus."

391
00:26:21.840 --> 00:26:26.983
In plain terms, 
this means that even if a parent element can't be focused, 

392
00:26:26.983 --> 00:26:30.454
if a child element can, the entire structure 

393
00:26:30.454 --> 00:26:34.080
can be styled as if the parent can be focused.

394
00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:40.240
That's why it can be applied to the unordered list element, 
instead of an anchor tag.

395
00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:45.209
Typically unordered list elements can't receive focus, 

396
00:26:45.209 --> 00:26:50.313
but because the list can contain an element 
like a link that can receive focus, 

397
00:26:50.313 --> 00:26:53.440
the list will respond to the focus-within class.

398
00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:57.374
Here's a small demonstration. 

399
00:26:57.374 --> 00:27:01.360
The markup for each of these menus is exactly the same.

400
00:27:01.360 --> 00:27:06.190
You can confirm as much by going to the CodePen, 
linked in the slide. 

401
00:27:06.190 --> 00:27:11.140
The only difference is the use of 
the focus-within selector. 

402
00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:15.360
You can see that on the left, 
the sub-menu elements

403
00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:21.193
for the About Us menu item aren't reachable by keyboard. 

404
00:27:21.193 --> 00:27:24.231
However, on the right you can tab through them 

405
00:27:24.231 --> 00:27:26.320
as you would the top level links.

406
00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.932
Here is an example in context. 

407
00:27:30.932 --> 00:27:33.916
The Admissions and About elements are links 

408
00:27:33.916 --> 00:27:39.680
with buttons to toggle sub-menus next to them as siblings, 
symbolized by the carrots.

409
00:27:40.800 --> 00:27:42.878
Without JavaScript enabled, 

410
00:27:42.878 --> 00:27:46.960
you can see how a visitor 
might traverse the menu items

411
00:27:46.960 --> 00:27:51.600
just with a keyboard and of course, 
they can still use a mouse as well.

412
00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:56.688
There are still some improvements we can make to this though. 

413
00:27:56.688 --> 00:28:00.968
For instance, maybe a visitor doesn't want to 
tab through every single item 

414
00:28:00.968 --> 00:28:03.840
of every single sub-menu to find the one they want.

415
00:28:05.040 --> 00:28:08.803
In this menu, maybe they want to tab to the 
student life sub-menu 

416
00:28:08.803 --> 00:28:11.966
without going through all the others.

417
00:28:11.966 --> 00:28:16.925
Now for that we need to start talking about JavaScript. 

418
00:28:16.925 --> 00:28:20.879
We can definitely get some accessibility improvements 

419
00:28:20.879 --> 00:28:24.082
to this type of menu if we add JavaScript. 

420
00:28:24.082 --> 00:28:26.912
In this project when a button is clicked, 

421
00:28:26.912 --> 00:28:31.360
the aria-expanded state changes from 
true to false or vice versa.

422
00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:35.358
The CSS is then set up so that the button's icon 

423
00:28:35.358 --> 00:28:37.840
will be changed depending on the state.

424
00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:42.115
This provides both visual and auditory context 

425
00:28:42.115 --> 00:28:44.800
for a site's visitors as they use the menu.

426
00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:52.790
However, one group that we haven't really talked about 
is developers themselves. 

427
00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:55.285
We might create a plug-in or library 

428
00:28:55.285 --> 00:28:58.320
that has technically excellent accessibility,

429
00:28:58.320 --> 00:29:01.500
but if it's hard for a developer who's 
beginning their career 

430
00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:04.169
to use the JavaScript or CSS that's included, 

431
00:29:04.169 --> 00:29:07.360
they may choose to avoid using 
the project altogether.

432
00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:13.183
The JavaScript or CSS for that matter, 
for this project, 

433
00:29:13.183 --> 00:29:17.534
doesn't require any additional dependencies or libraries. 

434
00:29:17.534 --> 00:29:22.560
Not only that, 
but in the context of WordPress the relevant script

435
00:29:22.560 --> 00:29:27.971
or styles can be enqueued directly from 
Composer's vendor directory. 

436
00:29:27.971 --> 00:29:32.779
This means that developers 
don't need any additional front-end tooling

437
00:29:32.779 --> 00:29:35.518
or bundling libraries to get started. 

438
00:29:35.518 --> 00:29:41.360
All that's required, 
is that they follow a typical WordPress workflow to enqueue dependencies.

439
00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:49.760
Once the script is properly enqueued 
it also has a very small external API.

440
00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:56.160
There's a configuration object which only has two properties, 
both of which are optional.

441
00:29:57.120 --> 00:30:02.918
In order to use the navigation JavaScript, 
there's only one method you need to know. 

442
00:30:02.918 --> 00:30:08.351
This means developers with a wide range of experience can 
use this in their projects. 

443
00:30:08.351 --> 00:30:12.723
This approach may be less flexible 
than something with a larger API. 

444
00:30:12.723 --> 00:30:15.986
However, I believe in this context it's a good trade-off, 

445
00:30:15.986 --> 00:30:20.880
because developers with a wide range of experience 
will be able to use it more quickly.

446
00:30:21.600 --> 00:30:27.760
In fact, as a university, 
sometimes we have student developers who work on our projects.

447
00:30:29.840 --> 00:30:33.635
The init method in the JavaScript 
starts by defining which menu 

448
00:30:33.635 --> 00:30:41.416
the JavaScript should apply to. 
It then removes the no-js CSS class from that menu. 

449
00:30:41.416 --> 00:30:46.890
Finally, it runs a method to setEventListeners 
on the menu and the document. 

450
00:30:46.890 --> 00:30:51.124
The setEventListeners method 
attaches listeners to menu items 

451
00:30:51.124 --> 00:30:54.880
and prepares them to pass events 
to an eventDispatcher.

452
00:30:55.840 --> 00:31:01.360
The dispatcher determines the type of event 
and routes it to a particular eventHandler.

453
00:31:02.720 --> 00:31:06.960
Once the event is properly dispatched to the handler, 
it's responsible

454
00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:10.080
for the logic to set the state 
of menu items and properties.

455
00:31:11.120 --> 00:31:16.160
Depending on the state of the menu, 
eventListeners are also added to the document,

456
00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:21.920
so people can close open sub-menus, 
with the escape key or by clicking outside the menu area.

457
00:31:24.240 --> 00:31:28.150
Here are two of the event handlers 
that are part of the JavaScript. 

458
00:31:28.150 --> 00:31:32.781
They're divided so that they can 
manage mouse or focus events separately. 

459
00:31:32.781 --> 00:31:35.284
And while I was working on the project, 

460
00:31:35.284 --> 00:31:40.773
I found it was best to keep mouse, 
keyboard, and focus events separate from each other. 

461
00:31:40.773 --> 00:31:44.583
That way I could handle exceptions 
for each type of event while 

462
00:31:44.583 --> 00:31:47.440
encapsulating other parts of the code for reuse.

463
00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:52.344
One thing to note here, 
is that these menu 

464
00:31:52.344 --> 00:31:56.270
follow the disclosure design pattern for navigation menus. 

465
00:31:56.270 --> 00:31:59.723
As I understand it, 
in terms of keyboard support, 

466
00:31:59.723 --> 00:32:03.623
this means that they're required to do three things:

467
00:32:03.623 --> 00:32:06.238
Move among items with the Tab key, 

468
00:32:06.238 --> 00:32:11.615
be able to select and activate items 
once they're focused with the Space or Enter key, 

469
00:32:11.615 --> 00:32:13.840
and close items with the Escape key.

470
00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:19.760
This is very different than 
an element with the Menu ARIA role. 

471
00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:24.303
The Menu ARIA Role requires 
more types of keyboard interaction, 

472
00:32:24.303 --> 00:32:27.071
such as the ability to use arrow keys. 

473
00:32:27.071 --> 00:32:29.453
However, in the example linked in the slide 

474
00:32:29.453 --> 00:32:34.994
(Well it doesn't appear to be linked in the slide, sorry about that. 
We'll get that later.),

475
00:32:34.994 --> 00:32:38.698
the markup is trying to create something more 

476
00:32:38.698 --> 00:32:42.160
like an application menu for a text editor.

477
00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.761
If it turns out that I'm completely wrong about this, 

478
00:32:44.761 --> 00:32:49.105
and that I need to add more keyboard support to the menus, that's okay. 

479
00:32:49.105 --> 00:32:53.630
The JavaScript is flexible enough to 
allow more types of keyboard events. 

480
00:32:53.630 --> 00:32:57.505
The event routing would require only a few additional cases. 

481
00:32:57.505 --> 00:33:03.330
From there I could add appropriate event handlers 
without too much difficulty, I hope. 

482
00:33:03.330 --> 00:33:06.974
In any event, I think it's always worth going back to review 

483
00:33:06.974 --> 00:33:10.320
projects from the past and see how they can be updated.

484
00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:14.031
Earlier this morning I read an article about WCAG 2.2 

485
00:33:14.031 --> 00:33:17.380
and for all I know I'll need to 
bring this project up-to-date

486
00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:20.400
to conform at some point to that, 
or a future version.

487
00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:28.332
In any event, here you can see the effect 
the JavaScript has on keyboard navigation. 

488
00:33:28.332 --> 00:33:31.255
A visitor can now select among different sub-menus, 

489
00:33:31.255 --> 00:33:33.840
however they like, with a mouse or a keyboard.

490
00:33:34.720 --> 00:33:38.370
Once the sub-menu is open, 
the next key press on the tab key

491
00:33:38.370 --> 00:33:40.560
will take visitors to the sub-menu.

492
00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:44.889
You can also see the relevant icon 
stays changed as well, 

493
00:33:44.889 --> 00:33:47.440
until someone leaves and closes the menu.

494
00:33:48.880 --> 00:33:53.120
This is done by tying the CSS to the aria-expanded attribute of the toggle.

495
00:33:55.200 --> 00:33:58.756
Here are just a few resources collected into one place. 

496
00:33:58.756 --> 00:34:02.344
I listed a few of the themes this project is part of, 

497
00:34:02.344 --> 00:34:06.745
just to demonstrate how it can be styled in different contexts. 

498
00:34:06.745 --> 00:34:10.727
This variety is why I wanted to 
make sure that the project was portable 

499
00:34:10.727 --> 00:34:14.463
and which is why we chose to bundle it as a Composer package. 

500
00:34:14.463 --> 00:34:17.459
I thought it would also be helpful to give a few 

501
00:34:17.459 --> 00:34:20.112
code resources and documentation as well. 

502
00:34:20.112 --> 00:34:25.040
You can browse the repo we use and if you like, 
contribute to help improve it.

503
00:34:27.360 --> 00:34:32.471
To wrap things up, there's still quite a lot to do, 
even after so much time. 

504
00:34:32.471 --> 00:34:36.560
Web Accessibility standards 
continue to be updated and refined.

505
00:34:37.120 --> 00:34:40.800
Plus, as I've shown, 
there's at least one thing that I've missed and need to revise.

506
00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:45.760
Personally, I want to make sure that 
I stay informed and engaged

507
00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:50.080
with issues around accessibility, 
so I can be of service to the people who visit us.

508
00:34:51.280 --> 00:34:55.888
To finish up, I'd like to thank all of you for being here with me. 

